com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers
Class BuildRequestWrapper

java.lang.Object
  com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers.WrapperBase
      com.urbancode.ubuild.scripting.wrappers.BuildRequestWrapper

public class BuildRequestWrapper
extends WrapperBase

Scripting class to give limited access to BuildRequest information. This is exposed as 'request' in some notification scripts.

Examples:

To get the name of the build request: 

    request.getName()
To get the id of the build request: 
    request.getId()
To get the request type of the build request: 
    request.getRequestType()
To get the name of the requester for the build request: 
    request.getRequesterName()
To get the status of the build request: 
    request.getStatus()
To get the user for the build request: 
    request.getUser()
To get the project for the build request: 
    request.getProject()
To get the workflow case of the build request: 
    request.getWorkflowCase()
To get the workflow of the build request: 
    request.getWorkflow()
To get the job trace of the build request: 
    request.getJobTrace()
To get a link to the build request: 
    request.getUrl()
To get a Map of all properties on the build request: 
    request.getProperties()
To get a specific property name 'specific.property' on the build request: 
    request.getProperties().get("specific.property")
If you are using velocity scripts for Notification Templates, you don't have to use the full method name for getters: 
    request.name
    request.id
    request.url
    request.requestType
    request.requestName
    request.status
    request.user
    request.project
    request.workflowCase
    request.workflow
    request.jobTrace
To display all request properties in a notification: 
    Request Properties:
    #set($requestProperties = $request.properties)
    #foreach($propName in $requestProperties.keySet())
        $propName: $requestProperties.get($propName)
    #end
If you are trying to retrieve some build request properties in a process, you would prefix the property with 'request/' For example, to get the status for a build request: 
    ${p:request/status}
To get information like the project name from the build request, you might need to chain some of these calls together. First, you would have to get the project and then get the name. For example: 
    ${p:request/project/name}
To get a specific property name 'specific.property' on the request: 
    ${p:request/properties[@name='specific.property'}
To get all property values based on the property name, you can use the functions startsWith, contains and matches: 
    ${p:fn:startsWith(request/properties, 'prefix')}
    ${p:fn:contains(request/properties, 'text')}
    ${p:fn:matches(request/properties, 'prefix.*')}
